WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.840
Everybody at the NBME got me in the room.

00:00:02.700 --> 00:00:03.600
We're making a difference.

00:00:04.720 --> 00:00:07.060
Because what I pitched to the state was
when you think

00:00:07.060 --> 00:00:09.800
about the way that we are rolling out
AI in healthcare,

00:00:09.800 --> 00:00:12.460
it's the same way we rolled out
EMRs 20 years ago.

00:00:12.740 --> 00:00:15.300
Twenty years ago, we just let the market
do whatever it's wanted, right?

00:00:15.640 --> 00:00:18.800
Now there are 117 EMR systems
in Kentucky

00:00:18.800 --> 00:00:20.740
and not a single one
talks to each other.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:22.020
That is a real number.

00:00:23.420 --> 00:00:27.260
And so what if we—and, and—we are facing
a healthcare crisis,

00:00:27.260 --> 00:00:29.900
the scope of which we can't even
comprehend right now,

00:00:30.540 --> 00:00:34.440
because of the big beautiful bill,
210,000 patients in Kentucky

00:00:34.440 --> 00:00:36.720
are about to lose
their health insurance, right?

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:39.140
There are 35 hospitals that are now
under threat of closure.

00:00:39.960 --> 00:00:41.500
If AI is going to
revolutionize healthcare,

00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:42.420
who does it for them?

00:00:42.820 --> 00:00:44.280
Because they could barely
keep the lights on.

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:47.380
So let's do it for them, right?

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:50.480
What if we provided healthcare AI
as a service?

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:54.280
One single institution—the state—
we get it together,

00:00:54.560 --> 00:00:55.660
we do it all, right?

00:00:56.180 --> 00:00:59.100
Every predictive model,
remote patient monitoring,

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:00.920
we do the whole thing.

00:01:01.220 --> 00:01:03.580
We find all of those cancers.
We bring them in.

00:01:03.880 --> 00:01:05.500
All of your A1Cs greater than nine

00:01:05.500 --> 00:01:07.500
who haven't followed up
with their primary care doctor

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:09.700
in a year, two years—
bring them back in.

00:01:10.580 --> 00:01:12.180
All of that health data exists

00:01:12.180 --> 00:01:13.680
on your health information exchange.

00:01:14.140 --> 00:01:15.940
What if we build
an intelligence layer

00:01:15.940 --> 00:01:17.320
that sat over the top of that,

00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:19.560
constantly crawling through that data,

00:01:19.980 --> 00:01:22.440
looking for signals,
looking for ways to make you better?

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:24.560
It's the OSCE grader.

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:26.500
It's just got a different face.

00:01:27.280 --> 00:01:28.140
And so this was the pitch.
